Lagos –  Following the public holiday declared by Federal Government on Monday, April 2, 2018 for the celebration of Easter, trading in the Nigerian Stock Market was for four days as against the usual five trading days in a week. During the week under review, activities on the floor of The Nigerian Stock Exchange(NSE) ended on a negative note as both the All-Share Index (ASI) and market capitalisation depreciated by 1.60 per cent week-on-week to settle at 40, 841.14 points and N14.753 trillion respectively. In all, a total turnover of 1.765 billion shares worth N26.562 billion in 20, 265 deals were traded last week by investors compared to a total of 2, 328 billion shares valued at N28.927 billion that exchanged hands in the previous week in 25,530 deals. All sectoral indices and group stock trackers finished lower during the week. Consequently, the financial services sector (measured by volume) led the activity chart with 1.468 billion shares valued at N18.707 billion traded in 12, 850 deals; thus contributing 83.18 per cent and 70.43 per cent to the total equity turnover volume and value respectively. The conglomerate industry followed with 127.882 million shares worth N623.871 million in 971 deals whereas the turnover of consumer goods stood at 69.868 million shares valued at N6.189 billion in 2, 930 deals. Specifically, trading in the top three equities namely: Zenith Bank, Access Bank and United  Bank for Africa (measured by volume) accounted for 543.758 million shares worth N9.739 billion in 3, 533 deals, contributing 30.81 per cent and 36.66 per cent to the total equity turnover volume and value correspondingly. Similarly, 19 equities appreciated in price during the week; lower than 40 of the previous week, 53 equities depreciated in price, higher than 40 equities of the preceding week while 99 equities remained unchanged higher than 61 equities recorded in the earlier week. 0 comments Do you get a good or bad response from your wife after making love? Discov